Project Title: Transforming Early Childhood Education: Creating Socially Just Global Learning Environments through Place Based Practices
additional information attach: Nganga and Kambutu StatementofWork__2023.doc, Revised Nganga and Kambutu StatementofWork__2023.pdf
additional information prop:
Attached is a draft proposal for the vision grant 



Statement of Work (SOW)

Spencer Foundation Vision Planning Grant

Period of Performance: 7/1/2024-6/30/2025

Title: Transforming Early Childhood Education: Creating Socially Just Global Learning Environments through Place Based Practices
The University of Wyoming will be a partner on this 12-month Spencer Foundation Vision planning grant. Dr. Lydiah Nganga and John Kambutu, Co-Investigators, will oversee and build on connections with Wind River Reservation- Wyoming (indigenous education-USA) on-going research and professional development, and follow up studies in early childhood care previously done in collaboration with Kenyan educators and education centers, and families with young children and intermediate grades. Dr. Nganga and Dr. Kambutu will provide a summary document that describes the cross-cultural collaborative research design and methodology used to write the 3.5-million-dollar Spencer Vision Implementation Grant that is the outcome of the planning grant. They will develop and make recommendations for the research at Wind River Reservation- Wyoming, US and Kenya. This will be drawn from in-depth interviews, workshops and  dialogues with educators, school leaders, families, and communities  in the respective areas.  Lydiah Nganga and John Kambutu will be responsible for coordination of Wind River Reservation and will coordinate three Kenyan educators  who have already extended an invitation to  work in collaboration with theirs schools and families. The Kenya team will apply for permission from their districts. Dr. Lydiah Nganga has an IRB for Wind River Reservation research  ( from the university of Wyoming). The protocol Number has been uploaded. 
 
Dr. Lydiah Nganga is Professor in the School of Teacher Education 
Dr. John Kambutu is Professor in the School of Teacher Education 

They are co-investigator on the planning grant working alongside the Principal Investigator, Dr. Jamie Sisson at the University of South Australia. John and Lydiah  will attend bi-weekly virtual (i.e., Zoom) 1-hour grant team meetings as well as monthly Zoom meeting or onsite  with colleagues. They will attend implementation grant work sessions hosted by the Center for Research on Social and Educational Inclusion (CRESI) at the University of South Australia. They will also travel to Kenya to meet with Kenyan researchers.   John and Lydiah and not requesting additional salary or course release time to write the implementation grant or attend planning grant and implementation grant meetings.  They are requesting travel funds  from the grant to  help cover cost identified above. 


Principle Investigator/submitting Institution: Jamie Sisson, University of South Australia 
Principal Investigator/submitting Institution: Samara Akpovo, University of Tennessee

additional information prop:
The DOE Funding Opportunity Announcement (FOA) will ultimately require 5 fillable PDF forms to be uploaded to Grants.gov. 

I am conscious that I may be using a different version of Adobe Acrobat Reader to Research Services. So, I was unsure whether it would be more useful to Research Services to include the 5 fillable PDFs (mostly completed) or just the attachments that will need to be added to those PDFs. I have therefore include BOTH. 

The 5 fillable PDFs are titled Form-A-* Form-B-*, etc. and the attachments are called, e.g., Form-B-Field7-* where "Form" matches the letter I've assigned to the fillable PDF and "Field" refers to the field on that form where the attachment will be attached. 

Hopefully that all makes sense!

Prime Sponsor: Bureau of Reclamation/Department of the Interior
full proposal title: Highly selective and scalable hollow fiber sorbent for rapid and complete removal of heavy metals from acid mine drainage-impacted water
proposal opportunity name: Desalination and Water Purification Research Program: Research Projects
voluntary csjustification:
1st- BOR said “For institutions of higher education, non-Federal cost share is not required but highly encouraged.
2nd - According to BOR’s proposal ranking criterion (pg. 27 of the FOA), if we don’t provide cost share, the best score we can get is 90%, which will put our proposal at a bad place at the beginning within a very competitive system, now matter how good the proposal is 
3rd  -   NMT is the leading organization.  They asked us to provide the matching.  Please note that NMT provides real cash as a match, while we just use our research time as a match.
4th -   To reduce UW’s matching percentage, we have a company to provide 25% matching, while UW provides 25% matching.  Please note that typical DOE FOAs ask at least 20% matching.  A lot of DOE proposals show more than 20% matching, although we do not do it.  

The cost-effectiveness versus the expected benefits of the potential project includes –
Firstly, we have much higher chance to win the award because we will not lose 10 score point if we do NOT provide matching according BOR (funding organization).  Otherwise, we just waste time to prepare the proposal.  The competition is very strong.
Secondly, any water projects (including this one) is very important to Wyoming because Wyoming is lacking in water resources.  Frankly speaking, water projects are more important than energy projects in Wyoming.  Wyoming is rich in energy resources; however, it is lacking in water resources.  As a matter of fact, I just met the leader of Laramie Drinking Water Treatment Plant in last week, I was very taken back by knowing how poor Laramie’s drinking water resources are when Mike (manager) talked to me how much effort Laramie city has made and has paid to purchase water right to guarantee the water supply for Laramie people in every year.

international travel details:
The project team has budgeted $21,000 in Year 2 for three researchers to travel internationally for a conference and/or institutional collaboration to learn more about approaches taken abroad to circular CM/REE recovery from waste streams and we will present on our preliminary findings for feedback if possible. Many institutions in 
E urope in particular have a more advanced understanding of the role for circular economies and waste stream use in the context of CM/REE. Europe also has similar interests in securing a supply chain with reliable transatlantic allies such as the United States. The team may travel to Norway to continue critical minerals collaborations that will be established during E. Phillips’s Fulbright project in 2025. It is also possible that the project team will travel to France in support of Tara Righetti’s international research efforts.

Routing Comment: Total Project Cost and total Sponsor costs are the same and cost share is included. Please ensure that the correct numbers are listed, if not already.
voluntary csjustification:
Per the proposal call: "Cost sharing or matching is not required for this program; however, a voluntary cost share is strongly encouraged. CESU partners are encouraged to show the difference between their formal Negotiated Indirect Cost Rate and the 17.5% rate agreed upon as a CESU partner as a voluntary cost share."

The normal negotiated federal indirect cost rate for the University of Wyoming (UW) is 44.5%. However, UW is a CESU partner. As such, the indirect cost rate for this project will be 17.5%. We have included matching funds based on the difference between these two indirect cost rates (i.e., 44.5% - 17.5% = 27%). These matching funds are derived by multiplying the percent difference between the indirect rates (i.e., 27%) by the indirect cost base (total direct costs minus student tuition/fees).

Project Title: Montana CMS Survey

additional information prop:
We were contacted directly by the client to do this project.  Following are details provided by them:

Good afternoon!

So, I included a PowerPoint overview of the HCBS measures set that CMS is, "proposing." I've also included the CMS CAHPS Home and Community Based Services Survey, as well as the data analysis guide. This hopefully will give you a better picture of what we are looking at and what it will take to accomplish. We also haven't been given the complete picture from CMS yet, but this is as much information as we have at the moment while reading between the lines. Feel free to ask any questions or if you have any concerns. Thank you!

Sample size: With approximately 2400 members on waiver, a confidence level of 95% with a +/-5% margin of error would require a recommended sample size of 332.
Mode: Based on the survey type/analysis guide, I would think the best results would come from a phone call, with a similar approach as the Montana Medicaid survey. However, we are definitely open to ideas from the subject matter experts.
Contact List: We can provide a random sample and contact list for those sample members.
Timeline: Completed annually, our first waiver year out of five waiver years, would begin next year.

Project Title: Collaborative project: Late Miocene paleoenvironmental conditions leading to catastrophic whale mass death assemblage in northern Chile
discipline category: Geosciences, Atmospheric Sciences, and Ocean Sciences
foreign collaboration details: Drs. Clementz and McFarlin will work with Drs. Gutstein, Chavez Hoffmeister, and Valenzuela Toro (see letters of collaboration in ) along with their students will conduct a series of surveys of exposures at Cerro Ballena and Mina Fosforita to assess changes in mammal abundance and diversity over time. Information from these surveys will be augmented by identification and description of previously collected material that is currently curated at the Paleontological Research Institute in Caldera and awaiting preparation. With assistance of Drs. Chavez Hoffmeister and Valenzuela Toro, we will combine data from museum collections with new specimens acquired at the field sites to provide a robust and comprehensive interpretation of faunal change in the late Miocene and Pliocene.
foreign shipment details: We will be shipping field equipment (rock hammers, bruntons, sample bags) to Caldera for use in the collection of sediment and fossil samples.
full proposal title: Collaborative project: Late Miocene paleoenvironmental conditions leading to catastrophic whale mass death assemblage in northern Chile
international travel details: We are planning for two multi-week field trips to the Caldera Basin in Chile for the collection of sediment samples and fossils for this project.

Project Title: Norcross NSF Collaboration
full proposal title: Collaborative Research: Fear in the forest: Human-induced fear and its impacts on biodiversity and ecosystem processes in a North American deciduous forest
noi admin notes: Accepted anytime, the PI has been working in the proposal for a few months.
proposal opportunity adtl info:
3. Collaborative Proposals

A collaborative proposal is one in which investigators from two or more organizations wish to collaborate on a unified research project. Collaborative proposals may be submitted to NSF in one of two methods: as a single proposal, in which a single award is being requested (with subawards administered by the lead organization); or by simultaneous submission of proposals from different organizations, with each organization requesting a separate award. In either case, the lead organizationï¿½s proposal must contain all of the requisite sections as a single package to be provided to reviewers (that will happen automatically when procedures below are followed). All collaborative proposals must clearly describe the roles to be played by the other organizations, specify the managerial arrangements, and explain the advantages of the multi-organizational effort within the Project Description.

a. Submission of a collaborative proposal from one organization

The single proposal method allows investigators from two or more organizations who have developed an integrated research project to submit a single, focused proposal. A single investigator bears primary responsibility for the administration of the grant and discussions with NSF, and, at the discretion of the organizations involved, investigators from any of the participating organizations may be designated as co-PIs. Note, however, that if awarded, a single award would be made to the submitting organization, with any collaborators listed as subawards. (See Chapter II.C.2.g(vi)(e) for additional instructions on preparation of this type of proposal.)

If a proposed subaward includes funding to support postdoctoral researchers, the mentoring activities to be provided for such individuals must be incorporated in the supplemental mentoring plan outlined in Chapter II.C.2.j.

b. Submission of a collaborative proposal from multiple organizations

Simultaneous submission of proposals allows multiple organizations to submit a unified set of certain proposal sections, as well as information unique to each organization as specified below. All collaborative proposals arranged as separate submissions from multiple organizations must be submitted via FastLane. For these proposals, the project title must begin with the words "Collaborative Research:ï¿½ If funded, each organization bears responsibility for a separate award.

Project Title: Permafrost dataset integration of satellite maps with historical topological maps
additional information prop:
This project addresses a critical dataset gap in climate change research by processing traditional historical maps and extracting information so that they become compatible with modern geospatial analytical tools, focusing on the permafrost regions of Siberia, Russia, and Alaska, United States. Permafrost plays a vital role in the global carbon cycle, and its thawing can release large quantities of greenhouse gasses, accelerating climate change. However, existing datasets lack the long-term historical context required to fully understand permafrost dynamics. We work to extend the temporal dimension of the permafrost dataset, offering valuable insights into the historical trends and better understanding how climate and permafrost changes are interlinked.
We aim to develop AI-based image processing techniques on digitized historical maps and excavating essential parameters such as surface topography, small ice/water body geometrics and other labeled features in maps that are important for tracking permafrost changes. Our methods will involve using convolutional neural networks to automate tasks such as georeferencing, contour mapping, texture analysis and pattern search, as well as recognizing written texts. Once extracted and validated, we will make this dataset compatible with geospatial tools and support existing efforts in permafrost spatial analysis using satellite imagery.
In alignment with the FAIR Data Principles, the dataset will be made Findable, Accessible, Interoperable, and Reusable (FAIR), ensuring it serves as a valuable, publicly available resource for the global climate research community. By filling a critical gap in permafrost data, this project will contribute to more accurate climate models and support long-term monitoring and adaptation strategies.

Project Title: CO2 capture
chemical agents list: 1,2 expoxybutane; Polyethylenimine
foreign collaboration details: The University of Wyoming (UW) will collaborate with Asahi Kasei (AK) to evaluate the feasibility of using an ionic liquid (IL) catalyst (EMmimNTf2) as a catalyst to improve the CO2 adsorption and desorption performances of modified PEI supported on porous silica (PS), MPEISoPS, proposed by AK, when the sorbent is used for direct air capture (DAC). The modifier proposed by AK (or used in literature) is 1,2 expoxybutane (called EB instead of 1,2 EB in Choi’s paper1). The functional groups and moieties of EB, PEI, and PS and their interactions and their impact on the catalytic function of the IL (only ppm level usage) for CO2 capture are unknown, especially because MPEISoPS contains high amount of EB, will be preliminarily evaluated.
foreign shipment details: According to the agreement between UW and the Japanese company, the  CO2 capture test data will be sent to the company.

proposal opportunity adtl info: The wgbglc all wildlife committee considers projects that benefit any fish and wildlife species other than bighorn sheep, mule deer, elk, and moose.  However, the committee will consider proposals for projects targeting those species if additional benefits to other species or their habitats are clearly articulated.  Although the all wildlife fund is the primary wgbglc funding source for projects focusing on pronghorn and state wildlife action plan (swap) priorities, the committee has chosen not to identify specific project or species priorities when accepting proposals.  The committee has funded projects that focus on research, monitoring, species or habitat restoration, equipment purchases, public outreach and education, and conservation easements, but retains the flexibility to entertain other requests.  Project funding derived from the wgbglc all wildlife fund sometimes accounts for a small, but important, component of larger projects and is often leveraged to obtain additional matching funds.  Funding awards from the all wildlife committee are generally less than $20,000.  Project proposals containing well-written narratives, clear and concise budgets, evidence of strong partnerships, and well-defined objectives and timelines for project completion have the best chance of funding.  Swap implementation projects should note the species of greatest conservation need most likely to benefit from the project and any relevant priorities identified in the swap that will be addressed.
